<subSubSection id="C320D285FFC1FFBAC1DAFA56FCD91C3A" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B85810EFFC1FFBAC1DAFA56FCD91C3A" blockId="17.[151,1438,583,1630]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="B94E5D1CFFC1FFBAC1DAFA56FEE91F8D" bold="true" box="[198,320,1487,1513]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species shares with 
<taxonomicName id="4C3AFA8DFFC1FFBAC371FA49FCA51F8D" box="[621,780,1488,1513]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="attenuatus">
<emphasis id="B94E5D1CFFC1FFBAC371FA49FCA51F8D" box="[621,780,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">D. attenuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the unusual feature of red xanthines and differs only in having a very much smaller costal band apical spot and a less extensively dark midfemur. There is a remote possibility that this is merely the dimorphic male form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3AFA8DFFC1FFBAC256F984FC431C52" box="[842,1002,1565,1590]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="attenuatus">
<emphasis id="B94E5D1CFFC1FFBAC256F984FC431C52" box="[842,1002,1565,1590]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">D. attenuatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It should also be noted that reddish xanthines are a known variant of some more common species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
